And so forth, fully justifying the writer's motto from Cicero, De Finibus: “Fortuita Concursu hoc fieri, mirum est.‘' It may seem that the mirthful element is not overpowering. But “gentle Dulness ever loves a joke''; and in 1766 this one, in modern parlance, “caught on.'‘ “Cross readings'' had, moreover‚ one popular advantage: like the Limericks of Edward Lear, they were easily imitated. What is not so intelligible is, that they seem to have fascinated many people who were assuredly not dull. Even Johnson condescended to commend the aptness of the pseudonym, and to speak of the performance as “ingenious and diverting.'‘ Horace Walpole, writing to Montagu in December 1766, professes to have laughed over them till he cried.
